data.title: USA Football Announces Select Team Rosters To Compete in Los Angeles at 2024 Select Bowl
data.text:
More than 200 athletes chosen from qualifying events nationwide to compete in Olympic-style flag football

INDIANAPOLIS, IND. & LOS ANGELES, CALIF. – USA Football, the sport’s governing body and a recognized sports organization of the U.S. Olympic & Paralympic Committee (USOPC), is proud to announce the 2024 Select Teams that will compete at Dignity Health Sports Park in Los Angeles from July 9-12 as part of the first annual Select Bowl.

The Select Bowl is the culminating event of USA Football’s National Team Development Program, which launched earlier in 2024. Select Team athletes gain access to U.S. National Team personnel, resources and experiences to hone their skills as they aim to earn invitations to U.S. National Team Trials. The top athletes competing at this year’s event will be eligible for invitations to Trials in 2025.

This year’s Select Bowl features 12U and 14U divisions for boys and girls, a 16U girls division and a 20U women’s division. Each division consists of four teams that will compete against each other in games that will be streamed on HomeTeam Live, a streaming service available at app.hometeamlive.com.

The National Team Development Program expands USA Football’s National Team Pathway by exposing elite athletes to Olympic-style flag football, U.S. National Team standards and resources and other elite athletes competing to represent the U.S. on the world’s stage.

Flag football will make its Olympic debut when the Summer Games comes to Los Angeles in 2028. The sport’s popularity internationally and domestically is exploding. According to the NFL, more than 20 million athletes play the sport across 100 countries. This year’s International Federation of American Football’s (IFAF) Flag Football World Championship will be the largest in history.

Flag football’s reach is also expanding in the U.S. USA Football research shows the number of boys and girls ages 6-17 playing flag football increased 38% from 2014-23, reaching a peak of more than 1.6 million this past year. Additionally, participation among girls ages 6-12 increased 222% during that time.

There are also opportunities for girls and women to play flag football competitively for high school and college programs. Eleven states, including California, sanction girls flag football as a varsity sport. Women’s flag football at the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) level features college scholarships and a national championship.
